A practical framework keeps early pregnancy decisions largely with patients and clinicians, sets any later limits in clear, medically workable terms, and includes explicit, non-punitive exceptions for threats to life or serious health, rape or incest, and severe fetal conditions. Lasting common ground comes from pairing any legal line with real prevention and support—easy access to contraception and accurate education, plus prenatal/postpartum care, paid leave, childcare, and adoption and disability resources—so fewer pregnancies become crises and fewer families are left without options.
